author: Garrett Stallsmith
message:
I asked my boss about what projects we could do and this is what he came back to me with.
1 Streamline our printing process
Context: We currently have to manually print posters whenever there is a conference or symposium. Automating this would save a lot of time.

2 Help me build an app to get rid of everybody being an administrator
Context: Sometimes faculty want to install an app on their own, but are denied because they do not have admin access. We solve this by manually adding them as a local admin. They want it so the user can ask and we can just grant it instead of getting a ticket and having to go somewhere and do something. Automating this would save a lot of time.

3 I would also like more help with QR code solutions in our science labs
Context: The IT team is currently working on a storage system for lab resources using qr codes. The idea is to use qr codes to create what are essentially maps to keep track of data. For example, if a lab takes fifty samples in fifty individual pipets it would be very useful to tell where and what everything is simply by scanning a slab of samples with your phone.

4 Remotely managing all of the bios settings and security
Context: We have to do this manually and it is a big time suck


Personally, I think the QR code project would be the most fun. There is also already some time put into the idea so we wouldn't be starting from scratch.

message:
Lastly, I did some work on the existing codebase. If you want to try it out, you can clone my branch "Ashton" on the github. Below are the steps to get the results images from a picture of QR codes. 

1. Clone Repo

author: None
message: 2. (Create virtual environment if not in one) python3 -m venv virtualenv

author: None
message: 3. (Enter virtual environment if just created)  source virtualenv/bin/activate

author: None
message: 4.pip install -r requirements.txt

author: None
message: 5. cd Scanner

author: None
message: 6. python MicroQRCodeScanner.py --image images/{whatever image you are inputting}

author: None
message: 7. The results, among some other json files that will be useful later, will be in the output folder titled "{imageName}.svg". You can open it via a live server or localhost as it may not show in vscode.

author: None
